<p class="image"><img src="images/H.DrizinGrave.jpg" alt="Herman Drizin Grave" /></p>
<p class="caption"><a href="https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/108343597/herman-drizin">Har Jehuda Cemetery, Upper Darby, Delaware County, Pennsylvania, USA</a>.</p>

<p>Herman Drizin was a Marine Second Lieutenant in the Second Battalion, Company ‚ÄúE,‚Äù 23rd Marines of the Fourth Division, Iwo Jima. He was killed in battle at the age of 24 in action on March 6, 1945. He was part of the first wave of Marines to land on Iwo Jima in February 1945. He was the leader of an attacking platoon that penetrated deep into the Japanese defense zone east of Iwo‚Äôs Sulphur pits in the early stages of the Iwo Jima battle. Herman and his squad of 13 men advanced a quarter of a mile into enemy lines, destroying three Japanese tanks and killing a dozen soldiers.</p>

<p class="image"><img src="images/H.DrizinCompensationFile.jpg" alt="World War II Veterans Service and Compensation File, from the Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania" /></p>
<p class="caption"><a href="https://search.ancestrylibrary.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?_phsrc=BjZ985&amp;_phstart=successSource&amp;usePUBJs=true&amp;qh=%2BdIRHx6ShGWkDLkJPmVyfQ%3D%3D&amp;gss=angs-g&amp;new=1&amp;rank=1&amp;msT=1&amp;gsfn=herman%20&amp;gsfn_x=0&amp;gsln=drizin&amp;gsln_x=0&amp;msypn__ftp=Pennsylvania,%20USA&amp;msypn=41&amp;catbucket=rstp&amp;MSAV=0&amp;uidh=ib1&amp;pcat=ROOT_CATEGORY&amp;h=253113&amp;dbid=3147&amp;indiv=1&amp;queryId=7a46dc9254b1f5a476e9587f7a71c6e2&amp;ml_rpos=2">World War II Veterans Service and Compensation File, from the Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania</a></p>

<p class="image"><img src="images/H.DrizinVUBasketball.jpg" alt="Herman Drizin Basketball Team photo" /></p>
<p class="caption"><a href="https://library.villanova.edu/Find/Record/vudl:534238">Belle Air Villanova College Yearbook 1943, page 224</a></p>

<p>Herman Drizin‚Äôs heroism and death was not learned of until a telegram was delivered to his parents‚Äô home on March 28, 1945 in the Frankford neighborhood of Philadelphia. He was one of 6,800 Marines who died at Iwo Jima, a battle which claimed the lives of hundreds of Japanese soldiers on the island.</p>

<p class="image"><img src="images/H.DrizinNationalJewishWelfareBoardDeathNotice.jpg" alt="Herman Drizin National Jewish Welfare Board Death Notification" /></p>
<p class="caption"><a href="https://search.ancestrylibrary.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?_phsrc=BjZ986&amp;_phstart=successSource&amp;usePUBJs=true&amp;qh=%2BdIRHx6ShGWkDLkJPmVyfQ%3D%3D&amp;gss=angs-g&amp;new=1&amp;rank=1&amp;msT=1&amp;gsfn=herman%20&amp;gsfn_x=0&amp;gsln=drizin&amp;gsln_x=0&amp;msypn__ftp=Pennsylvania,%20USA&amp;msypn=41&amp;catbucket=rstp&amp;MSAV=0&amp;uidh=ib1&amp;pcat=ROOT_CATEGORY&amp;h=25483&amp;dbid=2125&amp;indiv=1&amp;queryId=7a46dc9254b1f5a476e9587f7a71c6e2&amp;ml_rpos=1">National Jewish Welfare Board Death Notification</a>.</p>

<p>He attended Villanova University from 1943-1944 and was a star basketball player for the Wildcats. According to his nephew, Stephen Drizin, Herman was ‚Äúthe only Jew in Villanova‚Äôs starting five when he helped lead the Wildcats to a 19-2 record in 1942-3, the highest winning percentage of any team in their illustrious basketball history‚Äù (<a href="https://www.huffpost.com/entry/post_6962_b_4859367">The Huffington Post</a>).</p>

